    <h2>Approximate Nearest Neighbor (ANN)</h2>

    <p>Exact nearest neighbor search is O(n) - check every vector. ANN algorithms trade accuracy for speed.</p>

    <h3>HNSW (Hierarchical Navigable Small World)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Graph-based algorithm</li>
      <li>Multi-layer structure (like skip lists)</li>
      <li>Navigate from top layer (coarse) to bottom (fine)</li>
      <li>State-of-the-art accuracy/speed tradeoff</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="diagram-container">
      <pre class="mermaid" set:html={`graph TD
    A[Layer 2: Long jumps] --> B[Layer 1: Medium jumps]
    B --> C[Layer 0: Fine-grained search]
    A --> D[Query Vector]
    D --> E[Nearest Neighbors]
    
    style A fill:#3b82f6
    style B fill:#8b5cf6
    style C fill:#ec4899
      `} />
    </div>

    <h3>Other ANN Algorithms</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>IVF (Inverted File Index):</strong> Cluster vectors, search within clusters</li>
      <li><strong>LSH (Locality-Sensitive Hashing):</strong> Hash similar vectors to same buckets</li>
      <li><strong>Product Quantization:</strong> Compress vectors for faster comparison</li>
      <li><strong>FAISS:</strong> Meta's library combining multiple techniques</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Semantic Search</h2>

    <p>Search based on meaning, not just keywords:</p>

    <div class="diagram-container">
      <pre class="mermaid" set:html={`graph LR
    A[User Query] --> B[Embedding Model]
    B --> C[Query Vector]
    C --> D[Vector DB]
    E[Document Corpus] --> F[Embedding Model]
    F --> G[Document Vectors]
    G --> D
    D --> H[Top K Similar Docs]
    
    style B fill:#3b82f6
    style D fill:#8b5cf6
      `} />
    </div>

    <h3>Implementation Steps</h3>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Index Documents:</strong> Embed all documents, store in vector DB</li>
      <li><strong>Embed Query:</strong> Use same model to embed user query</li>
      <li><strong>Search:</strong> Find K nearest neighbors in vector space</li>
      <li><strong>Retrieve:</strong> Return original documents</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Hybrid Search</h3>
    <p>Combine semantic and keyword search:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Vector Search:</strong> Semantic similarity</li>
      <li><strong>BM25/TF-IDF:</strong> Keyword matching</li>
      <li><strong>Fusion:</strong> Combine scores (e.g., RRF - Reciprocal Rank Fusion)</li>
    </ul>

    <pre><code>Score = α × semantic_score + (1-α) × keyword_score
Where α ∈ [0, 1] controls the balance
</code></pre>

    <h2>Multimodal Embeddings</h2>

    <h3>CLIP (Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training)</h3>
    <p>Learns joint embedding space for text and images:</p>

    <div class="diagram-container">
      <pre class="mermaid" set:html={`graph LR
    A[Image] --> B[Image Encoder]
    C[Text] --> D[Text Encoder]
    B --> E[Image Embedding]
    D --> F[Text Embedding]
    E --> G[Shared Space]
    F --> G
    
    style B fill:#3b82f6
    style D fill:#8b5cf6
    style G fill:#ec4899
      `} />
    </div>

    <ul>
      <li>Trained on 400M image-text pairs</li>
      <li>Enables zero-shot image classification</li>
      <li>Cross-modal search (text→image, image→text)</li>
      <li>Foundation for Stable Diffusion, DALL-E</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Applications</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Image Search:</strong> "Find images of mountain sunsets"</li>
      <li><strong>Image Classification:</strong> Zero-shot with text labels</li>
      <li><strong>Content Moderation:</strong> Find inappropriate content</li>
      <li><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Similar products, content</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="callout best-practice">
      <div class="callout-title">✅ Best Practices</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Choose Right Model:</strong> Domain-specific vs general-purpose</li>
        <li><strong>Batch Embeddings:</strong> Embed in batches for efficiency</li>
        <li><strong>Normalize Vectors:</strong> For cosine similarity</li>
        <li><strong>Monitor Drift:</strong> Re-embed if data distribution changes</li>
        <li><strong>Cache Embeddings:</strong> Don't re-compute unnecessarily</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Key Terminology</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Embedding Space:</strong> High-dimensional vector space where semantics are encoded</li>
      <li><strong>Dense Retrieval:</strong> Semantic search using embeddings</li>
      <li><strong>Sparse Retrieval:</strong> Traditional keyword-based search (BM25, TF-IDF)</li>
      <li><strong>Quantization:</strong> Compress vectors for storage/speed</li>
      <li><strong>Re-ranking:</strong> Refine initial results with more expensive model</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Summary</h2>
    <div class="callout success">
      <div class="callout-title">✅ Key Takeaways</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Embeddings represent items as dense vectors so that “similar meaning” maps to “nearby in space.”</li>
        <li>Embedding types evolved from static word vectors to contextual and sentence-level representations.</li>
        <li>Similarity metrics (cosine/dot/distance) determine how “nearest neighbors” are computed.</li>
        <li>Vector databases use ANN indexing to search high-dimensional spaces efficiently at scale.</li>
        <li>Multimodal embeddings support cross-modal retrieval (e.g., text ↔ image).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h3>What is an embedding, in plain English?</h3>
    <p>An embedding is a list of numbers (a vector) that represents the meaning of a piece of text, image, or other data. Items with similar meaning end up with similar vectors — which means a computer can compare meaning numerically, not just by matching exact words.</p>

    <h3>Why do I need a vector database? Can’t I use a regular database?</h3>
    <p>Regular databases search by exact values or keywords. A vector database searches by similarity — finding the documents closest in meaning to your query. This powers semantic search, RAG pipelines, and recommendation engines. For small corpora, simpler in-memory tools work; a dedicated vector database earns its place when you need scale, persistence, or filtered similarity search.</p>

    <h3>What is semantic search and how does it differ from keyword search?</h3>
    <p>Keyword search matches exact words. Semantic search matches meaning. If a user searches “can’t log in,” keyword search misses documents about “authentication failure.” Semantic search, powered by embeddings, finds conceptually related content regardless of exact wording.</p>

    <h3>Which embedding model should I use for a new project?</h3>
    <p>For most English text use cases, a sentence transformer model is a solid starting point. For higher quality, API-based embedding models from OpenAI or Cohere are widely used. For multilingual or cross-modal retrieval, use models specifically trained for those tasks. Start small, measure retrieval quality, then upgrade if needed. <!-- REVIEW: model recommendations change frequently; verify current benchmarks --></p>

    <h3>When does approximate nearest neighbor (ANN) search matter?</h3>
    <p>Exact search checks every vector, which is too slow at scale. ANN indexes (like HNSW, used by most vector databases) find the closest vectors quickly by trading a small amount of precision for speed. ANN becomes necessary once your corpus exceeds tens of thousands of documents. Most vector databases handle this automatically.</p>

    <h2>Reflection Questions for Technical Leaders</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>A team proposes building a semantic search feature over your internal documentation. What questions would you ask before approving — about data quality, access controls, embedding model choice, and ongoing maintenance?</li>
      <li>Your product uses keyword search today. A colleague argues that switching to semantic search will improve user satisfaction. How would you structure a decision framework and success metrics to evaluate this change?</li>
      <li>You are selecting a vector database for a production RAG system. What factors beyond query speed would you consider — cost, data residency, licensing, operational complexity, and vendor support?</li>
      <li>Embeddings from one model are not directly comparable to those from a different model. What does this mean for system migrations and long-term maintenance planning?</li>
    </ol>

